        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We are mainly interested in the continuum emission. We sacrified a small fraction of the continuum bandwidth (20%) to observe at high spectral resolution the N2H+(1-0) line. If serendipitously detected, this line could provide an additional confirmation of the location of the CO snowline in the disk. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The angular resolution of 0.3arcsec is required to resolve the spectral index profile across the CO snowline. This angular resolution is within a factor of two of the full scale height at 100 AU from the star. It is expected not to resolve radially the feature we detected in Band 7 (at 0.45 arcsec resolution), which would decrease our sensitivity to it, while at the same time provide the best possible contrast between the unresolved feature and the smooth disk emission.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The goal of this proposal is to detect the excess emission in the 3mm continuum located at the CO snowline (0.8-1.0 arcsecond from the central star) in a protoplanetary disk. The excess emission is expected to have a relatively high contrast locally (&gt;30%), and to be unresolved in the radial direction of the disk. The expected peak flux of the feature we want to detect is estimated to be 0.1~mJy/beam and the required rms is ~0.01~mJy/beam. The peak flux from the inner disk in the 0.3 arcsec synthesized beam at 3mm is expected to be 3mJy, implying that we will require a dynamic range of ~300 in the final images.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
    </prj:ScienceGoal>
